## Workstream 2: Custom Span Attribute Access (Item 4 — CRITICAL)

Three complementary changes targeting different commands:

### 2A: `span view` — Use trace-items detail endpoint for ALL attributes

**Problem**: `span view` uses `/trace/{traceId}/` and cherry-picks 12 fields, dropping custom attributes.

**Solution**: For each requested span ID, make a supplementary call to `GET /projects/{org}/{project}/trace-items/{spanId}/?trace_id={traceId}&item_type=spans` which returns ALL attributes automatically. This is what the Sentry frontend does.

#### Files to modify

**`src/lib/api/traces.ts`** — Add new API function:

```typescript
/** Response shape from the trace-items detail endpoint */
type TraceItemAttribute = {
  name: string;
  type: "str" | "int" | "float" | "bool";
  value: string | number | boolean;
};

type TraceItemDetail = {
  itemId: string;
  timestamp: string;
  attributes: TraceItemAttribute[];
  meta: Record<string, unknown>;
  links: unknown;
};

/**
 * Fetch full attribute details for a single span.
 * Uses the trace-items detail endpoint which returns ALL attributes.
 */
export async function getSpanDetails(
  orgSlug: string,
  projectSlug: string,
  spanId: string,
  traceId: string
): Promise<TraceItemDetail> { ... }
```

**`src/commands/span/view.ts`** — After finding spans in the trace tree, fetch full details:

- After `getDetailedTrace()` finds the span in the tree (for structure/ancestors/children), call `getSpanDetails()` for each requested span ID
- Fetch details for all requested spans **in parallel** using p-limit (e.g., concurrency 5) to avoid sequential waterfall while respecting API rate limits. The command already accepts multiple span IDs (`sentry span view <trace-id> <span-id1> <span-id2>`), so this matters.
- Merge the flat attribute list into the JSON output as a `data` dict: `{ [attr.name]: attr.value }`
- For human output, show notable attributes in the KV table (skip internal ones like `precise.start_ts`, `received`, `hash`)

**`buildJsonResults()`** changes — add an `attributes` or `data` dict:

```typescript
function buildJsonResults(results: SpanResult[], traceId: string, details?: Map<string, TraceItemDetail>): unknown[] {
  return results.map((r) => {
    const base = { /* existing 12 fields */ };
    const detail = details?.get(r.spanId);
    if (detail) {
      // Convert attribute array to dict, filtering internal attrs
      base.data = Object.fromEntries(
        detail.attributes
          .filter(a => !INTERNAL_ATTRS.has(a.name))
          .map(a => [a.name, a.value])
      );
    }
    return base;
  });
}
```

